<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><channel><title>Concurrency on DailyPyTips</title><link>https://dailypytips.com/tags/concurrency/</link><description>Recent content in Concurrency on DailyPyTips</description><generator>Hugo -- 0.161.1</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Fri, 08 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://dailypytips.com/tags/concurrency/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Python Day 10: Python Is Not Parallel — Concurrency, Threads &amp; Async Explained</title><link>https://dailypytips.com/posts/python_metal_model/day10/</link><pubDate>Sat, 02 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://dailypytips.com/posts/python_metal_model/day10/</guid><description>&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You think Python runs things in parallel.
Most of the time, it doesn’t.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Today, you understand how Python handles concurrency, why it behaves the way it does, and how async actually works.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2 id="todays-goal"&gt;Today’s Goal&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By the end of today, you will:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Understand concurrency vs parallelism&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Learn about threads and the GIL&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Understand async/await internals&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Know when to use threading vs async vs multiprocessing&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h2 id="the-illusion"&gt;The Illusion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-python" data-lang="python"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nn"&gt;threading&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;def&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nf"&gt;task&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;():&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="nb"&gt;print&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;running&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;threading&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;Thread&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;target&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;task&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;start&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;()&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;You think:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>FastAPI Day 2: ASGI Changed Everything — Understanding Event Loops &amp; Concurrent Requests</title><link>https://dailypytips.com/posts/fastapi_mental_model/fastapi_event_loop_concurrency/</link><pubDate>Fri, 08 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://dailypytips.com/posts/fastapi_mental_model/fastapi_event_loop_concurrency/</guid><description>FastAPI only makes sense once you understand ASGI, event loops, and how async servers actually handle concurrent requests.</description></item><item><title>FastAPI Exists Because WSGI Couldn’t Scale Modern APIs</title><link>https://dailypytips.com/posts/fastapi_mental_model/fastapi_wsgi_vs_asgi/</link><pubDate>Fri, 08 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://dailypytips.com/posts/fastapi_mental_model/fastapi_wsgi_vs_asgi/</guid><description>Before FastAPI, Python web apps lived in a synchronous WSGI world. This post explains why ASGI changed everything.</description></item></channel></rss>